\begin_layout Subsection
Setup and Notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider a sequence of length 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 factor returns
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in1:T$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 can either include a constant for the intercept, or the data may already
 be centered.
 Factor returns are measured on a monthly basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An unobserved vector of latent returns for asset 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in1:N$
\end_inset

 is a function of a portion of these factors such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x_{it}= & f_{t}'\beta_{i}+\varepsilon_{it}^{u}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $K\times1$
\end_inset

 vector of exposures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For notational parsimony, and because other assets only enter the model
 through priors, drop the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 subscript.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The econometrician observes a length 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 vector of returns 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 will not equal 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is measured on a quarterly or annual basis or if the observations depend
 on multiple latent return realizations.
 Notably, the observation frequency may differ from the frequency of return
 realization.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
For convenience, use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $t\left[s\right]$
\end_inset

 to denote the corresponding value of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 for a particular 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Because the interval of time between observations is constant (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 periods), the mapping of observation period to latent return period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is described as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
t\left[s\right] & \equiv P+\Delta t+\left(s-1\right)*\Delta t
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The observed returns 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are a function of vector of unobserved (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

latent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) returns 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Intuition: The lags reflect a process whereby valuations of investments
 take up to the end of the lag window to be fully reflected in the returns
 of an asset.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The returns of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 follow a moving average process with 
\begin_inset Formula $P+\Delta t$
\end_inset

 terms plus measurement error.
 The moving average window is parameterized by 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 unrestricted coefficients and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 coefficients determined by restrictions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 represent the length 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 vector of restricted coefficients and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\phi}$
\end_inset

 be the length 
\begin_inset Formula $P+\Delta t$
\end_inset

 vector containing both restricted and unrestricted coefficients.
 Note that both 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\phi}$
\end_inset

 use indexing that is the reverse of typical, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\phi}_{P+\Delta t}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the coefficient on the contemporaneous value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 be the lag operator.
 Then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y_{s}= & \left(\tilde{\phi}_{1:\left(P+\Delta t\right)}\right)'x_{(t[s]-P-\Delta t+1):t[s]}+\varepsilon_{t}^{y}\\
= & \left(\tilde{\phi}_{\left(P+1\right):\left(P+\Delta t\right)}\right)'x_{\left(t[s]-\Delta t+1\right):t[s]}+\phi'x_{(t[s]-P):\left(t[s]-\Delta t\right)}+\varepsilon_{t}^{y}\\
= & \left(\tilde{\phi}_{\left(P+1\right):\left(P+\Delta t\right)}\right)'x_{\left(t[s]-\Delta t+1\right):t[s]}+\sum_{p\in1:P}\phi_{p}L^{P-p+\Delta t}x_{t[s]}+\varepsilon_{t}^{y}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If the contemporaneous term 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t[s]}$
\end_inset

 were unrestricted (say given a coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{P+1}$
\end_inset

), the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 would only be identified via priors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
To see the lack of identification, note that doubling 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and halving 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 would lead to the same prediction.
 Setting the coefficient on 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t[s]}$
\end_inset

 to 1 creates an implicit scaling restriction, but creates difficulties
 with respect to the scaling of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Restricting the coefficient to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t-\phi'1$
\end_inset

 preserves scaling at the cost of slightly increased in complexity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t>1$
\end_inset

, further restrictions help the identification.
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t=3$
\end_inset

, which corresponds to quarterly observed returns and monthly factor returns.
 If the following sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\phi}_{p}+\phi_{p-\Delta t}+\dots+\phi_{p-P}$
\end_inset

 does not add to 1.0, months that fall earlier in the quarter will have a
 different long-run impact on NAV than months later in the quarter.
 This combined with the above restriction implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 restrictions.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Assume the observed returns are defined in terms of a length 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 vector of latent variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Subject to regularity conditions, the use of measurement error in the model
 is without loss of generality with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 following a moving average process.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:ma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for a discussion.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The moving average can be written in two forms with matrix notation.
 To see this, consider the special case where both 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 have the same frequency.
 Then: 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\hat{y}=\Phi x= & X_{L}R\phi+x_{S}\\
\mkern-150mu \hat{y}=\begin{bmatrix}\phi_{1} & \cdots & \phi_{P} & \tilde{\phi}_{P+1} & 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \phi_{1} & \cdots & \phi_{P} & \tilde{\phi}_{P+1} & \cdots & \cdots & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \ddots & \ddots & \ddots & \ddots & \ddots & \ddots & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & \cdots & \cdots & \cdots & \phi_{1} & \cdots & \phi_{P} & \tilde{\phi}_{P+1} & 0\\
0 & \cdots & \cdots & \cdots & \cdots & \phi_{1} & \cdots & \phi_{P} & \tilde{\phi}_{P+1}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}x_{1}\\
x_{2}\\
\vdots\\
x_{T-1}\\
x_{T}
\end{bmatrix}= & \begin{bmatrix}x_{1} & x_{2} & \cdots & x_{P-1} & x_{P} & x_{P+1}\\
x_{2} & x_{3} & \cdots & x_{P} & x_{P+1} & x_{P+2}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots\\
x_{T-P-1} & x_{T-P} & \cdots & x_{T-3} & x_{T-2} & x_{T-1}\\
x_{T-P} & x_{T-P+1} & \cdots & x_{T-2} & x_{T-1} & x_{T}
\end{bmatrix}\left[R\right]\begin{bmatrix}\phi_{1}\\
\phi_{2}\\
\vdots\\
\phi_{P-1}\\
\phi_{P}
\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}x_{P+1}\\
x_{P+2}\\
\vdots\\
x_{T-1}\\
x_{T}
\end{bmatrix}\\
R\equiv & \begin{bmatrix}1 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 0\\
0 & 1 & \cdots & 0 & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & 1\\
-1 & -1 & \cdots & -1 & -1
\end{bmatrix}\\
\tilde{\phi}_{P+1}\equiv & 1-1'\phi\\
x_{S}\equiv & x_{t[s]\forall s}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
To generalize to quarterly data and other frequencies, recall 
\begin_inset Formula $t\left[s\right]\equiv P+1+\left(s-1\right)*\Delta t$
\end_inset

 and define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Phi_{sj}\equiv & \begin{cases}
\phi_{P-\left(t\left[s\right]-j-1\right)} & 1\le P-(t\left[s\right]-j-1)\le P\\
1-\left(\iota_{l}^{\phi}\right)'\phi & t\left[s\right]-\Delta t<j\le t\left[s\right]\\
0 & otherwise
\end{cases}\label{eq:Phi}\\
X_{Lsj}\equiv & x_{t\left[s\right]-\left(P-j\right)-1}\label{eq:XL}\\
\iota_{l}^{\phi}\equiv & \begin{cases}
1 & p+l\mod\Delta t=0\\
0 & otherwise
\end{cases}\label{eq:iotaphi}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The above matrix formulation can be generalized by only including rows of
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{L}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\left\{ t\left[1...S\right]\right\} $
\end_inset

 and adjusting the restriction matrix.
 The general version is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\hat{y}=\Phi x= & X_{L}R\phi+x_{S}\\
s.t.\\
x_{S}\equiv & X_{L}\iota_{\Delta t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{\Delta t}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 ones followed by 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 zeros, making 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{S}$
\end_inset

 the sum of the last 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{L}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The generative process is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p\left(y|rest\right)\sim & MN\left(X_{L}R\phi+x_{S},\frac{1}{\tau_{y}}I\right)\text{(equivelently}MN\left(\Phi x,\frac{1}{\tau_{y}}I\right))\\
p\left(x|rest\right)\sim & MN\left(F\beta+r,\frac{1}{\tau_{x}\tau_{y}}\Psi^{-1}\right)\\
p\left(\phi|rest\right)\sim & MN\left(\phi_{0},\frac{1}{\tau_{y}\tau_{\phi}}M_{0}^{-1}\right)\\
p\left(\beta|rest\right)\sim & MN\left(\beta_{0}+D^{-1}\beta_{0}^{\Delta},\frac{1}{\tau_{x}\tau_{y}\tau_{\beta}}\left[DA_{0}D\right]^{-1}\right)\\
d_{k}\equiv & (\gamma_{k}+(1-\gamma_{k})\frac{1}{v^{2}})^{0.5}\\
p\left(\gamma_{k}\right)\sim & Bern\left(\omega\right)\\
p\text{\left(\omega\right)}\sim & Beta\left(\kappa_{0},\delta_{0}\right)\\
p\left(\tau_{y}\right)\sim & Gamma\left(\alpha_{y0},\zeta_{y0}\right)\\
p\left(\tau_{x}\right)\sim & Gamma\left(\alpha_{x0},\zeta_{x0}\right)\\
p\left(\psi_{t}\right)\sim & Gamma\left(\nu/2,\nu/2\right)\\
p\left(\nu\right)\sim & Gamma\left(\alpha_{\nu0},\zeta_{\nu0}\right)\\
p\left(\tau_{\phi}\right)\sim & Gamma\left(\alpha_{\phi0},\zeta_{\phi0}\right)\\
p\left(\tau_{\beta}\right)\sim & Gamma\left(\alpha_{\beta0},\zeta_{\beta0}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

