\begin_layout Subsection
Reconciliation of 
\begin_inset Formula $q\left(\nu\right)$
\end_inset

 with Wand et al 2011
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The derivation of 
\begin_inset Formula $q\left(\nu\right)$
\end_inset

 should be equivalent to the solution given in Wand et al 2011 (WOPF) after
 accounting for the following differences:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
WOPF elect to use a uniform prior of 
\begin_inset Formula $Unif\left(\nu_{min},\nu_{max}\right)$
\end_inset

 instead of the gamma prior.
 A gamma prior seems more consistent with the rest of the model and has
 an advantage in not needing to truncate the support.
 However, for reconciliation purposes, this derivation will walk through
 the previous derivation using the Wand prior
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
WOPF parameterizes the variance instead of the precision (
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

), and hence the prior and posterior variables at each point in time are
 inverse gamma distributions instead of gamma distributions.
 This difference is innocuous.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Reconciling with WOPF equation 14:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\log\tilde{q}\left(\nu\right)= & E_{-\nu}\left[\frac{T\nu}{2}\log\left(\frac{\nu}{2}\right)-T\log\Gamma\left(\frac{\nu}{2}\right)+\sum_{t}\left(\frac{\nu}{2}\log\psi_{t}-\frac{\nu\psi_{t}}{2}\right)\right]+\tilde{c}_{1}^{\nu}\\
= & \frac{T\nu}{2}\log\left(\frac{\nu}{2}\right)-T\log\Gamma\left(\frac{\nu}{2}\right)+\frac{\nu}{2}\tilde{\eta}_{1}\\
q\left(\nu\right)= & \exp\left(\frac{T\nu}{2}\log\left(\frac{\nu}{2}\right)-T\log\Gamma\left(\frac{\nu}{2}\right)+\frac{\nu}{2}\tilde{\eta}_{1}\right)\tilde{\eta}_{2}\\
s.t.\\
\tilde{c}_{1}^{\nu}= & c_{1}^{\nu}-\sum_{t}\log\psi_{t}-\alpha_{\nu0}\log\zeta_{\nu0}+\log\Gamma\left(\alpha_{\nu0}\right)+\frac{1}{\nu_{\max}-\nu_{\min}}\\
\tilde{\eta}_{1}= & E\left[\sum_{t}\left(\log\psi_{t}-\psi_{t}\right)\right]\\
\tilde{\eta}_{2}= & \left(\int_{\nu_{\min}}^{\nu_{\max}}\exp\left(\frac{T\nu}{2}\log\left(\frac{\nu}{2}\right)-T\log\Gamma\left(\frac{\nu}{2}\right)+\frac{\nu}{2}\tilde{\eta}_{1}\right)d\nu\right)^{-1}\\
= & F\left(0,\nu,-\tilde{\eta}_{1},\nu_{\min},\nu_{\max}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Plugging in the property that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 equals the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{t}$
\end_inset

 from the Wand notation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
-\eta_{1} & =\sum_{t}\left(-E\left[\log\psi_{t}\right]+E\left[\psi_{t}\right]\right)\\
 & =\sum_{t}\left(E\left[\log a_{t}\right]+E_{t}\left[\frac{1}{a_{t}}\right]\right)\\
 & =C_{1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus using a uniform prior and accounting for the inverse gamma distribution
 leads to the same answer as WOPF.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Derivation of the precision 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0k}$
\end_inset

 given the expectation and variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\gamma k}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is helpful for deriving sequential priors.
 First, consider the simpler scenario where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}^{\Delta}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}$
\end_inset

 is matched to the expectation.
 This does not fully reflect the DGP, but it is a convenient and simple
 way to generate the prior:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\beta_{0}= & E\left[\beta_{k}\right]\\
Var\left(\beta_{k}\right)= & E\left[Var\left(\beta_{k}|\gamma_{k}\right)\right]+Var\left(E\left[\beta_{k}|\gamma_{k}\right]\right)\\
= & Var\left(\beta_{k}|\gamma_{k}=1\right)p_{k}^{\gamma}+Var\left(\beta_{k}|\gamma_{k}=0\right)\left(1-p_{k}^{\gamma}\right)+Var\left(E\left[\beta_{k}|\gamma_{k}\right]\right)\\
= & \frac{p_{k}^{\gamma}}{a_{0k}}+\frac{\left(1-p_{k}^{\gamma}\right)v^{2}}{a_{0k}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, consider the more complex scenario where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}$
\end_inset

 is given, and derive 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}^{\Delta}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E\left[\beta\right] & =\beta_{0}+p_{k}^{\gamma}\beta_{0}^{\Delta}+v\beta_{0}^{\Delta}\left(1-p_{k}^{\gamma}\right)\\
\implies\beta_{0}^{\Delta}= & \frac{E\left[\beta\right]-\beta_{0}}{p_{k}^{\gamma}+v*\left(1-p_{k}^{\gamma}\right)}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then apply the law of total variance to compute the implied 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0k}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Var\left(\beta_{k}\right)= & E\left[Var\left(\beta_{k}|\gamma_{k}\right)\right]+Var\left(E\left[\beta_{k}|\gamma_{k}\right]\right)\\
= & Var\left(\beta_{k}|\gamma_{k}=1\right)p_{k}^{\gamma}+Var\left(\beta_{k}|\gamma_{k}=0\right)\left(1-p_{k}^{\gamma}\right)+Var\left(E\left[\beta_{k}|\gamma_{k}\right]\right)\\
= & \frac{p_{k}^{\gamma}}{a_{0k}}+\frac{\left(1-p_{k}^{\gamma}\right)v^{2}}{a_{0k}}+p_{k}^{\gamma}\left(\beta_{0}+\beta_{0}^{\Delta}\right)^{2}+\left(1-p_{k}^{\gamma}\right)\left(\beta_{0}+v\beta_{0}^{\Delta}\right)^{2}-E\left[\beta_{k}\right]^{2}\\
a_{0k}= & \frac{p_{k}^{\gamma}+\left(1-p_{k}^{\gamma}\right)v^{2}}{Var\left(\beta_{k}\right)-p_{k}^{\gamma}\left(\beta_{0}+\beta_{0}^{\Delta}\right)^{2}-\left(1-p_{k}^{\gamma}\right)\left(\beta_{0}+v\beta_{0}^{\Delta}\right)^{2}+E\left[\beta_{k}\right]^{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Approximate moving average equivalence 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:ma"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
While the employment of measurement error may seem odd given that returns
 are generally considered factual, it is without loss of generality with
 respect to modeling a moving average process.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the sequential dynamics of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 (if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t>0$
\end_inset

, model some values of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 as unobserved).
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y_{t}= & \left(\Delta t-\sum_{p=1}^{P}\phi_{p}\right)x_{t}+\sum_{p=1}^{P}\phi_{p}L^{P-p}x_{t-1}+\epsilon_{t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To start, rescale the series towards the cannonical MA representation.
 Difference the new series:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
z_{t}\equiv & \left(y_{t}-\mu\right)\left(\Delta t-\sum_{p=1}^{P}\phi_{p}\right)^{-1}\\
z_{t}= & \left(1+\sum_{p=1}^{P}\varphi_{P-p+1}L^{p}\right)x_{t}+\varepsilon_{t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assume the state variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 has an unconditional variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then autocovariance is characterized as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\gamma_{0}= & \left(1+\sum_{p=1}^{P}\varphi_{P-p+1}^{2}\right)\sigma_{x}^{2}+\sigma_{\varepsilon}^{2}\\
\gamma_{1}= & \sigma_{x}^{2}\left(\varphi_{P}+\sum_{p=2}^{P}\varphi_{P-p+1}\varphi_{P-p+2}\right)\\
\gamma_{2}= & \sigma_{x}^{2}\left(\varphi_{P-1}+\sum_{p=3}^{P}\varphi_{P-p+1}\varphi_{P-p+3}\right)\\
\gamma_{s}= & \begin{cases}
\left(1+\sum_{p=1}^{P}\varphi_{P-p+1}^{2}\right)\sigma_{x}^{2}+\sigma_{\varepsilon}^{2} & s=0\\
\sigma_{x}^{2}\left(\varphi_{P-s+1}+\sum_{p=s+1}^{P}\varphi_{P-p+1}\varphi_{P-p+1+s}\right) & 0<s\le P-1\\
\sigma_{x}^{2}\varphi_{1} & s=P\\
0 & P<s
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Wold decomposition theorem states that for any covariance stationary
 process, the following form is equivalent up to the second moment:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
z_{t}= & \sum_{j=0}^{\infty}a_{j}\eta_{t-j}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

As the autocovariance function is unique and terminates, the Wold representation
 is characterized as
